{"cursor":"23758","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\nThe 'Whyte notation' for classifying steam locomotives by wheel arrangement was\ndevised by Frederick Methvan Whyte and came into\nuse in the early twentieth century encouraged by an editorial in American\nEngineer and Railroad Journal (December 1900). Whyte's system counts the number\nof leading wheels, then the number of driving wheels, and finally the number of\ntrailing wheels, groups of numbers being separated by dashes. Other\nclassification schemes, like UIC classification and the French, Turkish and\nSwiss systems for steam locomotives, count axles rather than wheels.\n\nThus, in the Whyte Notation a locomotive with two leading axles (and thus four\nwheels) in front, then three driving axles (six wheels) and then one trailing\naxle (two wheels) is classified as a 4-6-2.\n","linknr":848,"url":"Whyte_notation","recorded":1362553972,"links":120,"instances":["locomotive","locomotive","locomotive","locomotive","locomotive"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Locomotive classification systems","Notation"],"headings":["Method","Limitations","Naming","See also","References","Further reading","Other websites"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/Locotypes.gif/200px-Locotypes.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/Locomotive_classification--Colvin_1906--300dpi.jpg/200px-Locomotive_classification--Colvin_1906--300dpi.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2b/WheelArrangement_0-2-2.svg/27px-WheelArrangement_0-2-2.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1f/WheelArrangement_2-2-0.svg/30px-WheelArrangement_2-2-0.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/WheelArrangement_2-2-2.svg/35px-WheelArrangement_2-2-2.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/t